descript.abstract: This dataset represents active use park areas(1) in San Diego County. It primarily consists of publicly owned parks, but may contain privately owned park land (2).
descript.purpose: A joint project between the County of San Diego, the District Attorney's Office, and SANDAG, this dataset represents an ongoing effort to map all active park areas(1) for monitoring registered sex offenders who are required to live farther than 2000 feet from parks "where children gather"(3).
descript.supplinf:
(1). San Diego County Code of Regulatory Ordinances SEC 810.102.(a) (a) "Active Recreational Uses" means recreation facilities occurring on level or gently sloping land (maximum 10%) restricted for park and recreation purposes in a planned development which are designed to provide individual or group activities of an active nature common to local parks in San Diego County, including, but not limited to, open lawn, sports fields, court games, swimming pools, children's play areas, picnic areas, recreation buildings, dance slabs, and recreational community gardening. Active Recreational Uses do not include natural open space, nature study areas, open space for buffer areas, steep slopes, golf courses, riding and hiking trails, scenic overlooks, water courses, drainage areas, water bodies (lakes, ponds, reservoirs), marinas and boating areas, parking areas, and archaeology areas.
(2) A private facility should not be included if it is privately held and includes any of the following: (a)The facility is access constrained or physically limits use based upon a membership or owner vetted acceptance as a criteria for use, such as a private club, gym, or golf course, amusement park, etc. (b)The facility is privately held and is only temporarily used as a active use recreational venue through means of a permit or established convention among the owners of the facility, e.g., a parking lot could be used once a year as a carnival staging area. Temporary can be defined here as no more than 10 days of use ‘active recreational use’ in any calendar year. If a private facility is in continual use as an active recreational use and does not apply a vetting criteria for its use (as described in 2.a) - it should be included.
(3). "Jessica's Law" SEC. 21. Section 3003.5 of the Penal Code is amended to read: 3003.5 (b) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, it is unlawful for any person for whom registration is required pursuant to Section 290 to reside within 2000 feet of any public or private school, or park where children regularly gather.

overview.dsoverv: This dataset was originally produced from three data sets: SANDAG Landcore, Thomas Brothers digital data, and the County of San Diego Department of Parks and Recreation's Parks layer. The first step was to select all active parks (7601) and active beaches (7604) from Landcore's existing land use and put them into a new layer. Next, all Landcore parcels whose centroids were in a Thomas Brothers identified park and was not already identified as a Landcore active park or beach were added to this layer. Next, any Landcore parcels whose centroids were in the County of San Diego's park layer and were not already included in the previous steps were added to the layer. The data was dissolved to merge parcels that comprised a single park. The result of the dissolve is that the individual parcels that make up a park were lost but the outside boundaries of the parks should line up with parcel boundaries. The data was also compared to SanGIS's City Parks layer and any parks not yet included were added. The data was then compared to aerial imagery. Several polygons that were not obviously parks were deleted, as well as areas within larger parks that could not considered "Active Use"1.
